headline.main: The Last Survivor of Peary's Expedition to the North Pole; Donald Baxter MacMillan

results.snippet: PROVINCETOWN, Mass., April 6 -- Still erect as a stanchion on a schooner's fo'c'sle, Rear Adm. Donald B. MacMillan, retired, "paced the deck" as usual today and reflected on the expedition that discovered the North Pole on this date 60 years ago.

results.abstract: NASA announces Armstrong will be 1st man to set foot on moon; Aldrin will follow Armstrong out of lunar module a few mins later; 2 astronauts will remain outside craft no more than 2 hrs and 40 mins during 22-hr stay on moon; will be restricted to area 50 to 100 ft from craft; plan to walk on lunar surface to test ability to move in lunar gravity, which is only 1/6 that of earth; will take soil samples; other planned experiments described

headline.main: Armstrong Designated as First To Set Foot on Lunar Surface

results.snippet: WASHINGTON, April 14 -- The first human being to set foot on the moon will be 38-year-old Neil A. Armstrong, according to space agency plans announced today.

headline.main: To Astronaut, School Was Never Like This

results.snippet: WALL TOWNSHIP, N. J., April 18 (AP) -- "Entrez, Rusty," said the sign on the door of the French class at Wall High School. Russell Louis Schweickart, the astronaut, entered and was immediately kissed by two girls.

results.lead_paragraph: Col. Frank Borman, commander of the Apollo 8 flight around the moon, said yesterday that the most important reason for pressing space exploration was to "challenge American technology and American industry" as has never happened, "except under the stress of war."
